         <div type="translation"
              ana="#b1"
              xml:id="zoor0099.translation"
              corresp="#zoor0099.transcription">
            <p>Monument of Seouda, (daughter) of Thadaios, who died having a good name and good
                    faith (at the age) of 40 years, in (the) year 306, on (the) 1st (day) of (the)
                    month Audynaios, on (the) 2nd day of the Lord (Monday). Be of good cheer,
                    Seouda, no one (is) immortal.</p>
         </div>
      </body>
      <back>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>The inscription provides the date as the 2nd day of the Lord (Monday), the 1st day of the month Audynaios in the year 306 according to the Era of the Province of Arabia, that is, December 17, 411 CE. The tombstone is one of about 700 discovered in Byzantine Zoora. The majority of the Greek tombstones from this location have been identified as Christian. This tombstone is in poor condition, suffering a break in its upper right corner, while its smoothed, inscribed surface is chipped in the lower left corner. The text, written predominantly in a round script with a few square exceptions, is engraved and painted over in red paint. A partially preserved outlined sun-disc, heavily drawn in red paint, appears above the inscription. The text contains both spelling and grammatical errors. The personal name Σεούδα is attested elsewhere in this corpus (no. 110) and is probably derived from the Arabic Sawad, meaning "blackness." The patronymic Θαδδέος is highly speculative, since only the first letter is clear.</p>
         </div>
